Mexican Stocks: Megacable, Penoles Gain; Telmex, Alfa Fall

-- B y   L e o n   L a z a r o f f
-- 
2011-03-11T21:38:25Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-03-11/mexican-stocks-coca-cola-femsa-gains-penoles-telmex-fall.html
The following companies had unusual
price changes in  Mexico  trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses and prices are as of 4 p.m. New York time.  The IPC index rose 0.6 percent to 36,091.22.  Coca-Cola Femsa SAB (KOFL MM), the largest Coke bottler in
Latin America, rose 0.3 percent to 91.17 pesos a day after
announcing plans to sell debt in Mexico this year. The soft-
drink bottler, controlled by Monterrey-based Fomento Economico
Mexicano SAB, didn’t provide a date or size of the sale in a
statement to the Mexico stock exchange.  Telefonos de Mexico SAB (TELMEXL MM), the nation’s largest
fixed-line provider, fell 2.1 percent to 10.18 pesos. The shares
have fallen 5.3 percent since Telmex said March 8 that it wants
to split its business in rural areas into a separate company
called Telmex Social. Telmex hasn’t contacted the government to
ask for permission to restructure.  Megacable Holdings SAB (MEGACPO MM), a telecom services
provider based in Guadalajara, Mexico, gained 2.1 percent to
26.93 pesos on volume 44 times its three-month average. Earlier,
Megacable increased as much as 9.5 percent.  Industrias Penoles SAB (PE&OLES* MM), Mexico’s largest
silver producer, rose 0.6 percent to 417.76 pesos. Silver
futures for May delivery gained 86.9 cents, or 2.5 percent, to
$35.935 an ounce. This week, the price increased 1.7 percent,
the seventh straight gain. The metal has more than doubled in
the past 12 months.  Alfa SAB (ALFAA MM), the world’s largest producer of
aluminum engine heads, fell 0.1 percent to 150.68 pesos. U.S.
applications for first-time  unemployment benefits  for the week
ended March 5 surpassed the median estimate in a Bloomberg
survey of economists. The U.S. is Alfa’s second-biggest revenue
source. General Motors Corp. and Ford Motor Co. are clients.  Cemex SAB (CEMEXCPO MM), the largest cement maker in the
Americas, rose 1.6 percent to 10.48 pesos after boosting its
convertible-bond sale by as much as 21 percent over what it
planned as the company seeks to reduce bank debt faster. Cemex
aims to sell as much as $1.67 billion of convertible bonds.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Leon Lazaroff in New York at 
